  "title": "The Distance Formula",
  "body": " The Distance Formula   Now that we know how to plot points on the coordinate plane, it is natural to ask how far apart two points are. There are various ways to measure the distance between two points, and in this course, we are talking about the shortest distance between two points. The shortest distance between two points is given by the Distance Formula. In this section, we will provide a proof of the Distance Formula and use the formula to solve various mathematical and applied problems.    Distances in the Real World  In the real world, people can't walk through objects; therefore, taking the shortest path between two points is often impossible. Traveling in a town or city is an example of this. Many neighborhoods are laid out in a square grid, and people can only travel along the roads which act as the sides of the squares. For example, in the following image, if a person wants to travel from point to point , they can travel two blocks east and one block north. The total distance traveled is three city blocks. This measure of distance is called the Taxicab Metric since it measures the distance a taxicab takes as it takes a passenger from point to point .   A grid of city blocks with a red line showing the path of a taxicab from point to point .   The taxicab travels two blocks east, turns north, and travels an additional block.    There are a couple problems with the Taxicab Metric.   In mathematics, we often want important concepts to be unique. In the Taxicab Metric, the shortest distance is not unique—there are three ways to travel from to in 3 city blocks.    The three ways to get from to in 3 city blocks.      The three minimum-length paths the taxicab can take.    The taxicab travels two blocks east, then turns north.      The taxicab travels one block east, turns north, and travels an additional block east.      The taxicab travels one block north, and then travels two blocks east.        The shortest distance between points and is the length of the line segment joining them.   A red, dashed line segment connects points A and B.    However, the idea of traveling via city blocks does give us enough information to find the shortest distance between and . If we call the intersection where the taxi turns left point , then the points , , and form the right triangle . This means that side has length 2 and side has length 1.   When we combine with , we get a right triangle.   Right triangle formed by points A, B, and C on a city grid.    Since we have a right triangle, we can use the Pythagorean Theorem to solve for side — the shortest distance from to : Therefore, the shortest distance from to is approximately 2.236 city blocks.    Proof of the Distance Formula   The Distance Formula   Let and be any two points on the coordinate plane. The distance between and is given by the formula    Points and with a dashed line segment connecting them. The dashed line segment is labeled with the Distance Formula.   Diagram showing a dashed line joining points A and B. The line is labeled with the Distance Formula.      It turns out that the Pythagorean Theorem is the key to finding a general formula for the Distance Formula. We are still traveling from point to point . If we draw a horizontal line through and a vertical line through point , the intersection of the horizontal line and vertical line is the point . The points , , and also form the right triangle .   formed by connecting the points , , and .   Right triangle formed by connecting points A, B, and C.    To use the Pythagorean Theorem, we need to measure sides and of . Fortunately, distances on vertical and horizontal lines are equivalent to finding distances on a number line. Since the points and are on the same horizontal line, to find the length of side , we find the difference of their first coordinates: . Since the points and are on the same vertical line, to find the length of side , we find the difference of their second coordinates: .   with the formulas and labeling the short and long legs, respectively.   Right triangle with legs labeled using coordinate differences.    Now, we have all the information required to compute the distance from to . The following calculation shows us how to compute the distance for any two points:     Instead of drawing a picture and using the Pythagorean Theorem every time we have to compute a distance, we can use the final line of the previous calculation to compute the distance directly. Since we are calculating a distance, we will use the letter instead of in the formula.     In a problem, it doesn't matter which point you call and which you call since and .    "
