  "body": " The Definition of Complex Numbers   When you learned numbers, you started off with the Counting (Natural) Numbers . Then you learned about zero and you had access to . Then you learned about negative numbers and expanded your list of numbers to the integers . Then you learned about fractions and expanded your knowledge of numbers to the rational numbers . Finally, you learned about radicals and numbers to expand your knowledge of numbers to the real number system. But your journey is not yet complete. There is one more layer to numbers you will learn in this section: complex numbers.    The Imaginary Number  If we try to solve the equation for , the square root method gives us . But, since we are not allowed to take the square root of negative numbers in the real number system, we simply say there is no solution. But when we say this, we mean there is no real solution; in other words, there is no value of on the real number line that will satisfy this equation.  So what do we know in this case? Well, since no number we have learned about so far can be a solution to , it has to be some other number we have not considered before. Let us call it for imaginary since we just made it up. This implies that , which implies that . This is how we define this number.   Definition of   The imaginary number  is the positive solution to the equation .    Powers of are really easy to calculate, and unlike real numbers, there are only four values you have to memorize since the powers cycle through four unique values.     The pattern continues forever like this. If we look at the first four exponents— —these are the possible remainders you get when you divide an integer by . Notice that the powers of that have the same remainder after dividing the exponent by will have the same value.  Now, we remind you of the following fact.   Divisibility Rule for 4   An integer is divisible by if its last two digits form a number that is divisible by .     Divisibility Rule in Terms of Remainders  In the language above, this means that a number is divisible by if you divide the last two digits by and get a remainder of .   It turns out that this rule also works for remainders as well. Therefore, if we divide the last two digits of a number by and look at the remainder we get, this tells us which power of to use.   Computing Powers of   To evaluate for any positive integer , complete the following steps.  Divide the last two digits of by using long division and determine the remainder. You should get , , , or .   The remainder tells you which power of to use from this list.         Compute a Power of   Compute .         First, we divide the last two digits of the exponent by and determine the remainder.   The long division of by . The remainder is equal to .    Since the remainder is equal to , we have that .      Complex Numbers  Now that we know about the number , we are ready to define complex numbers.   Complex Number   Let and be any real numbers. A complex number is any number of the form .    Do complex numbers really exist? The symbol was given the epithet “imaginary” since some mathematicians debated their existence before complex numbers were firmly established as a legitimate number system. It turns out that complex numbers are just another way to describe points in the coordinate plane. For example, the point can also be represented by the complex number . But there is a subtle difference. Instead of thinking of it as the corner of a rectangle, we think of as an arrow pointing from the origin to the point .   Two ways to visualize the point . In rectangular coordinates, it is represented as a dot. As a complex number, it is represented as an arrow pointing from to .   An arrow labeled 3+4i points from the origin to the point (3,4).    Complex numbers are very useful in describing things with circular motion, such as circles. Unfortunately, these types of models are just outside the scope of this course, but only barely. In fact, as you will see in a later course, we can use complex numbers to define a circle using a function, which is something we cannot do with rectangular coordinates.   "
